### User interaction

Users connected via SSH can send `^]` (*i.e.*, `Control¬†+¬†]`) during
their session to access the following TELNET control features:

* `]` ‚ÄĒ sends a literal `Control‚ÄĎ]` to the target TELNET host

* `0` ‚ÄĒ sends a literal `NUL` to the target TELNET host

* `A` ‚ÄĒ sends an IAC `AYT` (*Are You There?*) to the target TELNET host

* `B` ‚ÄĒ sends an IAC `BREAK` signal to the target TELNET host

* `C` ‚ÄĒ toggles the conversion of legacy host character mappings to
  UTF-8 (if enabled via the `--iconv` option)

* `I` ‚ÄĒ sends an IAC `INTERRUPT` signal to the target TELNET host

* `K` ‚ÄĒ toggles the transparent key remapping mode, which translates
  modern `xterm`/`VT320` movement key inputs to Emacs sequences:

  |             Input | Output        |
  |------------------:|:--------------|
  | `Control¬†+¬†Up`    | `Escape,¬†[`   |
  | `Control¬†+¬†Down`  | `Escape,¬†]`   |
  | `Control¬†+¬†Right` | `Escape,¬†f`   |
  | `Control¬†+¬†Left`  | `Escape,¬†b`   |
  | `Home`            | `Control¬†+¬†A` |
  | `Delete`          | `Control¬†+¬†D` |
  | `End`             | `Control¬†+¬†E` |
  | `Up`              | `Escape¬†+¬†v`  |
  | `Down`            | `Control¬†+¬†V` |
  | `Up`              | `Control¬†+¬†P` |
  | `Down`            | `Control¬†+¬†N` |
  | `Right`           | `Control¬†+¬†F` |
  | `Left`            | `Control¬†+¬†B` |

* `N` ‚ÄĒ sends an IAC `NOP` (*No Operation*) to the target TELNET host

* `S` ‚ÄĒ displays the status of the session, sharing information, and
  some statistics:

  ```plaintext
  >> LNK ‚ÄĎ The username '_gRSyWHxPcMp2MWvtmWWF' can be used to share this session.
  >> SSH ‚ÄĎ in:   58 B,   out: 4.82 KiB, in rate:   4 B/s, out rate: 381 B/s
  >> NVT ‚ÄĎ in: 4.82 KiB, out:   57 B,   in rate: 381 B/s, out rate:   4 B/s
  >> LNK ‚ÄĎ link time: 13s (Emacs keymap enabled)
  ```

* `X` ‚ÄĒ disconnects from the target TELNET host (and ends the SSH
  session)

### Connection sharing

* The user can share ūü§Ě the username presented above with others,
  allowing the session to be viewed live ūüĎÄ (read‚ÄĎonly) by one or more
  viewers:

  ```sh
  $ ssh _gRSyWHxPcMp2MWvtmWWF@proxybox

  CONNECTION from remote.com [18.17.16.15] started at 2025/07/15 08:22:55.
  This is a READ‚ÄĎONLY shared monitoring session.
  Send Control‚ÄĎ] to disconnect.
  ```

## Compressed logs

* By default, all session log files are compressed ūüóúÔłŹ automatically
  when the session terminates, and console log files are compressed
  when the log rolls over (*i.e.*, when starting a new day).

* When reviewing logs, administrators often need to search through all
  the past data, including through the compressed files. We recommend
  using [`ripgrep`](https://github.com/BurntSushi/ripgrep) (with the
  `‚ÄĎz` option) for this task.

## Using OpenSSH host keys

If you have existing [OpenSSH](https://www.openssh.com/) Ed25519, RSA,
or ECDSA host keys that you want to use with the proxy, you‚Äôll first
need to convert those keys to standard PEM format.

ūüö®¬†**NB**: These instructions *do not* include any specific details
for safe handling of key file permissions‚ÄĒwe assume you are `root`
and that you know what you‚Äôre doing!

1. Make a *copy* of the key files you wish to convert.  Be aware that
   these copies will be *overwritten* in the conversion process:

   ```sh
   cp /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key ssh_host_ed25519_key.tmp
   cp /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key ssh_host_rsa_key.tmp
   cp /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key ssh_host_ecdsa_key.tmp
   ```

2. Convert the keys (using `ssh‚ÄĎkeygen`) and rename them appropriately:

   ```sh
   ssh-keygen -p -m PEM -N '' -P '' -f ssh_host_ed25519_key.tmp
   mv ssh_host_ed25519_key.tmp ssh_host_ed25519_key.pem

   ssh-keygen -p -m PEM -N '' -P '' -f ssh_host_rsa_key.tmp
   mv ssh_host_rsa_key.tmp ssh_host_rsa_key.pem

   ssh-keygen -p -m PEM -N '' -P '' -f ssh_host_ecdsa_key.tmp
   mv ssh_host_ecdsa_key.tmp ssh_host_ecdsa_key.pem
   ```

## History

This is a from‚ÄĎscratch re‚ÄĎimplementation (in [Go](https://go.dev/)¬†ūüźĻ)
of an older legacy program of the same name.

The original software used a multi‚ÄĎprocess architecture and consisted
of nearly **15,000 lines** of haphazardly constructed code: ‚ČÖ14,000
lines of mostly [C‚ÄĎKermit](https://www.kermitproject.org/)¬†ūüźł (*yes,
the
[programming language](https://www.kermitproject.org/ckscripts.html)*)
and [`ksh93`](https://github.com/ksh93/ksh)¬†ūüźö (along with some C¬†ūüíĽ,
Python¬†ūüźć, and Perl¬†ūüź™) which was difficult to maintain, configure,
and securely install.

This new implementation uses many lightweight *Goroutines*¬†ūüöÄ instead
of spawning multiple processes, resulting in significantly improved
performance and reduced system overhead.

